ro (245PS), 580 Nm model replaced 500 Nm model in UK.\n\n=== Transmissions ===\n{|class=\"wikitable collapsible sortable\"\n|+Petrol engines\n!Model!!Years!!Standard!!Optional\n|-\n|A6 hybrid||2012\u2013||8-speed tiptronic||-\n|-\n|A6 2.0 TFSI (180PS)||2011\u2013||6-speed manual||multitronic\n|-\n|A6 2.0 TFSI (211PS)||2011\u2013||multitronic||-\n|-\n|A6 2.8 FSI (204PS)||2011\u2013||6-speed manual||multitronic\n|-\n|A6 FSI quattro (204PS)||2011\u2013||7-speed S tronic||-\n|-\n|A6 2.5 FSI (190PS)||2012\u2013||multitronic||-\n|-\n|A6 3.0 TFSI quattro (300PS)||2011\u2013||7-speed S tronic||-\n|-\n|A6 3.0 TFSI quattro (310PS)||2012\u2013||Saloon: 7-speed S tronic, 8-speed tiptronic<br/>Avant: 7-speed S tronic<br/>Allroad quattro: 7-speed S tronic||-\n|-\n|A6 L 2.8 35 FSI (220PS)||2012\u2013||multitronic||-\n|-\n|A6 L 2.8 35 FSI quattro (220PS)||2012\u2013||7-speed S tronic||-\n|-\n|A6 L 3.0 50 TFSI quattro (299PS)||2012\u2013||7-speed S tronic||-\n|-\n|S6 4.0 TFSI quattro (420PS, 450PS)||2012\u2013||7-speed S tronic||-\n|-\n|RS6 4.0 TFSI quattro (560PS, 605PS)||2012\u2013||8-speed tiptronic||-\n|}\n{|class=\"wikitable collapsible sortable\"\n|+Diesel engines\n!Model!!Years!!Standard!!Optional\n|-\n|A6 2.0 TDI||2011\u20132014||6-speed manual||8-speed multitronic\n|-\n|A6 2.0 TDI||2014\u20132018||6-speed manual||7-speed S tronic\n|-\n|A6 3.0 TDI (204PS)||2011\u20132014||6-speed manual||8-speed multitronic\n|-\n|A6 3.0 TDI (218PS)||2014\u2013||7-speed S tronic||-\n|-\n|A6 3.0 TDI quattro (204PS, 245PS)||2011\u20132014||7-speed S tronic||-\n|-\n|A6 3.0 TDI quattro (190PS, 218PS, 272PS)||2014\u20132018||7-speed S tronic||-\n|-\n|A6 3.0 TDI quattro (313PS, 320PS, 326PS)||2011\u20132018||8-speed tiptronic||-\n|}\n\nFor A6 Saloon 3.0 TFSI quattro (310 PS), 7-speed S tronic is used in UK model, 8-speed tiptronic is used in US, Canada models.\n\nA6 3.0 TDI quattro (313 PS) was sold as A6 3.0 BiTDI quattro in the UK.\n\n=== Safety ===\n{{Euro NCAP |year=2011 |overall_stars=5 |description=LHD, 4-door saloon |reference=http://www.euroncap.com/results/audi/a6/2011/435.aspx |adult_points=33 |adult_percent=91 |child_points=41 |child_percent=83 |pedestrian_points=15 |pedestrian_percent=41 |safety_points=6 |safety_percent=86}}\n\n===Marketing===\nAs part of Audi A6 Avant launch in the UK, BBH London, Knucklehead, The Whitehouse, The Mill produced the 'Hummingbird' TV commercial, directed by Daniel Barber. The commercial premiered during the ITV1's coverage of the Rugby World Cup. The commercial was to imagine what a bird designed by Audi would look like and to reflect the car's ultra-lightweight technology. Johann Strauss's 'Open Road, Open Sky' was sung by legendary American baritone and automobile lover John Charles Thomas. In addition, 60 second and 30 versions of the ads were supported by press, print and radio campaigns, as well as a presence on the Daily Telegraph's iPad app.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.adweek.com/news/advertising-branding/ad-day-audi-135326|title=Ad of the Day: Audi|work=AdWeek|accessdate=14 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.themill.com/work/audi-a6/hummingbird.aspx|title=The Mill|author=The Mill|work=The Mill|accessdate=14 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ca.adforum.com/agency/3874/press-releases/567|title=BBH & Audi launch charming new campaign to promote A6 Avant \u2013 Bartle Bogle Hegarty \u2013 Adforum.com|publisher=|accessdate=14 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nAs part of Audi A6 launch in Taiwan, 2011 Audi Fashion Festival featured the theme of 'A6- The sum of Progress', including Shiatzy Chen, Kiki Huang, Robyn Hung and an artistic jewelry brand, Chen Chan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jca.com.tw/en/portfolio_page.php?type=8&no=62|title=JC & Associates Communications, Inc.-case studies|publisher=|accessdate=14 July 2015|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150404134825/http://www.jca.com.tw/en/portfolio_page.php?type=8&no=62|archivedate=4 April 2015|df=}}</ref>\n\nAs part of 2013 Audi S6 sedan launch in the US market, 3 different versions of 'Prom' commercial were premiered during 2013 Super Bowl game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autoblog.com/2013/01/25/choose-your-own-adventure-in-audis-next-super-bowl-commercial/|title=Choose your own adventure in Audi's next Super Bowl commercial|author=Jonathon Ramsey|work=Autoblog|accessdate=14 July 2015}}</ref> The 60-second ad, created by Venables Bell & Partners, features a teenage boy. Voters were to decide their favourite version of the commercial 24 hours on Friday before the Super Bowl game, with winning entry shown on Saturday at Audi's YouTube channel and during the actual game at CBS.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/audis-super-bowl-spot-looks-213422886.html|title=Audi's Super Bowl Spot Looks Like A Taylor Swift Music Video For Dudes|date=23 January 2013|work=Yahoo Finance|accessdate=14 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.freep.com/article/20130123/BUSINESS01/130123029/1014/business01|title=Audi, Coke put Super Bowl ad endings in your hands|work=Detroit Free Press|accessdate=14 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nAs part of RS6 Avant launch, Audi Land of quattro Alpen Tour 2013 featured RS6 Avant begins on September 23, travelling across twelve driving stages in 6 countries (Klagenfurt \u2013 the capital of Carinthia, Austria, Monaco).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.audi-mediaservices.com/publish/ms/content/en/public/pressemitteilungen/2013/09/20/audi_land_of_quattro.html|title=Audi MediaCenter|work=Audi MediaCenter|accessdate=14 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn the Audi RS6 Avant TV commercial titled 'Perfect Fit', it featured a 2012 Audi R18 with the high downforce sprint bodywork in the guise of [[Audi R18]] e-tron quattro.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fourtitude.com/news/Audi_News_1/audi-r18-e-tron-quattro-stars-in-new-audi-rs-6-tv-commercial-perfect-fit/|title=Audi R18 e-tron quattro Stars in New Audi RS 6 TV Commercial \"Perfect Fit\"|work=Fourtitude.com|accessdate=14 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.motorsport.com/lemans/news/audi-r18-e-tron-quattro-featured-in-new-rs-6-tv-commercial/|title=Audi R18 e-tron quattro featured in new RS 6 TV commercial|work=Motorsport.com|accessdate=14 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n== {{anchor|C8|4K|fifth}}C8 (''Typ'' 4K, 2018\u2013present) ==\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name = Fifth generation (C8/4K)\n| image = 2018 Audi A6 TDi Quattro Front.jpg\n| production = 2018\u2013present\n| engine = [[Petrol engine|Petrol]]<br/>2.0 litre I4 TFSI 185 kW<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.caranddriver.com/news/a28247921/2019-audi-a6-20t-four-cylinder-photos-info/|title=The 2019 Audi A6 Gains a New Base Four-Cylinder Engine with 248 HP|work=[[Car and Driver]]|last=Golson|first=Daniel|date=2 July 2019|accessdate=3 July 2019}}</ref><br/>2.0 litre I4 TFSI 190 PS Mild Hybrid (MHEV)<br />3.0 litre V6 TFSI 250 kW<br/>2.9 litre [[Twin-turbo|TT]] V6 TFSI 336 kW (S6)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.caranddriver.com/news/a27112511/2020-audi-s6-photos-info/|title=2020 Audi S6 Drops the V-8, but Its Turbo V-6 Attempts to Assuage Us with More Torque|work=[[Car and Driver]]|last=Capparella|first=Joey|date=11 April 2019|accessdate=11 April 2019}}</ref><br>4.0 litre TT V8 TFSI 441 kW (RS6)<br/>[[Diesel engine|Diesel]]<br/>2.0 litre I4 TDI 150kW<br>3.0 litre V6 TDI 172 & 210 kW<br/>[[Plug-in hybrid]]<br/>2.0 litre I4 TFSI 185 kW with an electric motor (A6 55 TFSI e quattro)\n| transmission = 7-speed [[dual clutch]] [[S tronic]]<br/ >8-speed [[Automatic transmission|automatic]] [[tiptronic]]\n| wheelbase = {{convert|2924 |mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| length = {{convert|4939 |mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| width = {{convert|1886|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| height = {{convert|1457 |mm|in|1|abbr=on}}<br>Avant: {{convert|1467 |mm|in|1|abbr=on}}<ref>Audi A6 Avant 2018 Dimensions Carsized.com</ref>\n| assembly = {{Unbulleted list |Germany: Neckarsulm |China: Changchun (FAW-VW, A6L only)|India: [[Aurangabad, Maharashtra|Aurangabad]] ([[Audi India]])<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cardekho.com/india-car-news/indiabound-2019-audi-a6-herersquos-whatrsquos-new-21499.htm|title=India-bound 2019 Audi A6 - Here\u2019s What\u2019s New &#124; CarDekho.com|website=CarDekho|accessdate=November 27, 2019}}</ref>}}\n}}\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"150px\">\nFile:2018 Audi A6 TDi Quattro Rear.jpg|Rear view\nFile:Audi A6L 55 TFSIe Quattro 1Y7A5429.jpg|Audi A6L (China)\nFile:Audi A6 C8 Avant 50 TDI Quattro IMG 0909.jpg|Audi A6 Avant (Europe)\nFile:2018 Audi A6 S Line 40 TDi S-A 2.0.jpg|Audi A6 C8 S Line\nFile:2019 Audi A6 Avant TDi 40 Interior.jpg|Cockpit, A6 C8\nFile:Audi S6 C8 at IAA 2019 IMG 0305.jpg|Audi S6\n</gallery>\n[[File:Audi S6 C8 at IAA 2019 IMG 0302.jpg|thumb|Audi S6]]\n[[File:Audi S6 Avant C8 IMG 1974.jpg|thumb|Audi S6 Avant]]\n[[File:Audi RS6 Avant C8 at IAA 2019 IMG 0194.jpg|thumb|Audi RS6 Avant]]\n[[File:Audi RS6 Avant C8 at IAA 2019 IMG 0304.jpg|thumb]]\n[[File:Audi A6 Allroad Quattro C8 at IAA 2019 IMG 0770.jpg|thumb|Audi A6 Allroad]]\n[[File:Audi A6 Allroad Quattro C8 at IAA 2019 IMG 0298.jpg|thumb]]\n{{Expand section|date=March 2018}}\nThe new A6 was unveiled ahead of the [[Geneva Motor Show#2018|2018 Geneva Motor Show]], and went on sale in June 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://driving.ca/audi/a6/auto-shows/geneva-motor-show/the-2019-audi-a6-raises-the-bar-for-luxury-car-tech|title=The 2019 Audi A6 raises the bar for luxury car tech|date=2018-03-06|work=Driving|access-date=2018-03-07|language=en-US}}</ref> All engines are offered with a [[mild hybrid]] drivetrain that can reduce fuel consumption by up to 0.7 litres per 100 kilometres for the V6-engined vehicles. The A6 will be offered in 7 new exterior colors and 7 colors which are available in current models.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.autoguide.com/auto-news/2018/02/2019-audi-a6-arrives-packed-with-high-tech-features.html|title=2019 Audi A6 Arrives Packed with High Tech Features \u00bb AutoGuide.com News|date=February 28, 2018|accessdate=November 27, 2019}}</ref> Following the launch of the new A6, Audi officially stopped production of the preceding A6 and A7 TDI variants due to an investigation on newly discovered emissions cheating software.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thelocal.de/20180508/audi-halts-a6-production-over-new-emissions-cheating-report|title=Audi halts production of latest A6 model over 'new emissions cheating': report|date=May 8, 2018|website=www.thelocal.de|accessdate=November 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Avant ===\n{{Expand section|date=November 2018}}\nThe fifth generation of the A6 is also available as an 'Avant' (Audi terminology for a station wagon). High-performance variants of the 'Avant' will also be produced, with the S6 Avant arriving in 2019 alongside the RS6 Avant.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnet.com/roadshow/news/2019-audi-a6-avant-wagon-debut/|title=2019 Audi A6 gets an Avant version, wagon geeks rejoice|first=Kyle|last=Hyatt|website=Roadshow|accessdate=November 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.caranddriver.com/news/a19743967/avant-time-yes-theres-a-new-a6-wagon|title=Avant Time! Yes, There\u2019s a New A6 Wagon|first=Davey G.|last=Johnson|date=April 11, 2018|website=Car and Driver|accessdate=November 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.motor1.com/news/246515/new-audi-rs6-avant-spied/|title=New Audi RS6 Avant Spied With Barely Any Camouflage|last=Performance|first=Audi RS 6 Avant|website=Motor1.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-17}}</ref>\n\n=== Engines ===\nAll variants are offered in mild hybrid engines as standard. The A6 will get a 3.0L V6 with petrol direct injection and a single turbo EA839 engine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.carwow.co.uk/audi/a6|title=New Audi A6 Review|website=carwow.co.uk|accessdate=November 27, 2019}}</ref> A plug-in hybrid model A6 55 TFSI e quattro was revealed on October 21, 2019. It combines a {{Convert|252|PS|kW hp|abbr=on}} 2.0 L TFSI with a {{Convert|143|PS|kW hp|abbr=on}} electric motor. The combined system output is {{Convert|367|PS|kW hp|abbr=on}} and {{convert|500|Nm|lb\u00b7ft|1|abbr=on}} of torque. The car gets a 14.1 kWh battery pack that delivers a pure electric range of 53 km (32.9 mi).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.autodevot.com/2019/10/audi-a6-55-tfsi-e-quattro-plug-in-hybrid-53-km-pure-electric-range/|title=Audi A6 plugs-in, gets 53 km pure electric range|website=www.autodevot.com|accessdate=21 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Transmission ===\nAll variants comes with a 7-speed S-tronic DCT and 8-speed tiptronic automatic.\n\n===Markets===\n====North America====\n{{Missing information|section|North American launch|date=May 2018}}\nThe 2019 Audi A6 Sedan made its North American debut at the 2018 [[New York International Auto Show]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wheels.ca/news/2019-audi-a6-makes-north-american-debut/|title=Audi A6 Makes North American Debut|website=WHEELS.ca|accessdate=November 27, 2019}}</ref> At this time, Audi has stated that the A6 Avant will not be sold in the United States, however the new RS6 Avant will be sold in the US for the first time in 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.motor1.com/news/366159/audi-rs6-avant-debuts-america/|title=Audi RS6 Avant Finally Arrives In America With 591 Horsepower|last=Avant|first=Audi RS 6|website=Motor1.com|language=en|access-date=2019-10-04}}</ref> The A6 allroad is also on sale for the first time in the United States and Canada for the first time since 2005.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.audiusa.com/models/audi-a6-allroad|title=2020 Audi allroad|last=|first=|date=|website=www.google.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-04}}</ref>\n\n==== Asia ====\n* China - The fifth generation Audi A6L was listed for the Chinese market in January 2019. Engine choices available consist of two turbocharged petrol engines: a 2 litre unit and a 3 litre unit. Both are equipped with a 7 speed dual clutch gearbox as standard. Trim levels consist of the 40, 50 and 55 trims and are all TFSI models. Price ranges for the January 2020 exchange rate are between 409,800 yuan and 650,800 yuan (59,000 and 93,700 USD).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://car.autohome.com.cn/config/series/18.html#pvareaid=3454437|title=2019 Audi A6L (Chinese specifications)}}</ref>\n* India - The fifth generation of the Audi A6 will be the first generation of the A6 to be assembled and sold in India.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.autocarindia.com/car-reviews/2018-audi-a6-review-test-drive-408444|title=2019 Audi A6 review, test drive - Autocar India|website=www.autocarindia.com|language=en|access-date=2018-06-23}}</ref> It will launch in May 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.zigwheels.com/newcars/Audi/a6|title=Audi A6 Price 2019 (Check November Offers!), Images, Reviews, Specs, Mileage, Colours in India|website=ZigWheels.com|accessdate=November 27, 2019}}</ref>\n* Bangladesh - The fifth generation of the Audi A6 will be the first generation of the A6 to be sold in Bangladesh.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.autorebellion.com/2017/09/audi-dhaka-progress-motors-imports-ltd-press-meet-and-showroom-launch/|title=Audi Dhaka-Progress Motors Imports Ltd, Press meet and showroom launch|first=Saurin|last=Rahman|date=September 25, 2017|website=Auto Rebellion|accessdate=November 27, 2019}}</ref>\n* Thailand - The fifth generation of the Audi A6 will be the first generation of the A6 to be sold in Thailand.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bangkokpost.com/auto/1420494/new-audi-a6-gets-mild-hybrid-tech|title=New Audi A6 gets mild hybrid tech|first=Bangkok Post Public Company|last=Limited|website=www.bangkokpost.com|accessdate=November 27, 2019}}</ref>\n* Brunei - The A6 was launched since end of 2019/early 2020 in Brunei with offered its trims: 2.0-litre engine (40 TFSI) and 3.0-litre Quattro engine (55 TFSI).\n\n====Europe====\n\n==Use in China==\nAccording to Dunne & Company, a research company, as of 2011, purchases in China and Hong Kong make up about half of the 229,200 Audi A6s sold in the world. By 2012 many government officials in China began driving with Audi A6s. After a 1994 campaign from the Chinese government to have officials stop driving Mercedes stretch limousines, the officials began using black Audi A6 cars. Michael Wines of ''[[The New York Times]]'' wrote that \"More than a perk, the black Audi is a rolling advertisement for its occupant\u2019s importance and impunity in a nation obsessed with status.\"<ref>Wines, Michael. \"[https://www.nytimes.com/2012/11/18/fashion/in-china-audi-means-big-shot.html?_r=0 In China, \u2018Audi\u2019 Means \u2018Big Shot\u2019].\" ''[[The New York Times]]''. November 16, 2012. Retrieved on March 21, 2014.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commonscatinline}}\n*[http://www.audi.com/com/brand/en/models/a6.html Audi A6] at Audi corporate website\n*[https://www.facebook.com/groups/855673094551074/ Audi 6 Club] in Hong Kong. Free membership for owners and enthusiasts of A6, S6, RS6, and A7, S7, RS7.\n\n{{Audi}}\n{{Audi vehicles timeline (Europe)}}\n{{Audi vehicles timeline (North America)}}\n\n[[Category:Audi vehicles|A6]]\n[[Category:All-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n[[Category:Euro NCAP executive cars]]\n[[Category:Executive cars]]\n[[Category:Front-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n[[Category:Vehicles with CVT transmission]]\n[[Category:Mid-size cars]]\n[[Category:Plug-in hybrid vehicles]]\n[[Category:Sedans]]\n[[Category:Station wagons]]\n[[Category:1990s cars]]\n[[Category:2000s cars]]\n[[Category:2010s cars]]\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 1994]]\n", "name_user": "TKOIII", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:cats", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Audi_A6"}
{"title_page": "Huangshan City", "text_new": "{{More footnotes|date=March 2014}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|name                   = {{raise|0.2em|Huangshan}}\n|native_name            = {{lower|0.1em|\u9ec4\u5c71\u5e02}}\n|native_name_lang = zh-Hans\n|official_name          = \n|nickname               = \n|settlement_type        =[[Prefecture-level city]]\n|total_type             = <!-- to set a non-standard label for total area and population rows -->\n|motto                  =\n<!-- images and maps  ----------->\n|image_skyline          = HuangShanCity.JPG\n|imagesize              = \n|image_caption          = Reconstructed old town, Song Street\n|image_map              =  Location of Huangshan Prefecture within Anhui (China).png\n|mapsize                =  \n|map_caption            =  \n|image_map1             = \n|mapsize1               = \n|map_caption1           = \n|image_dot_map          =\n|dot_mapsize            =\n|dot_map_caption        =\n|dot_x =  |dot_y =\n|pushpin_map            = \n|pushpin_label_position = \n|pushpin_map_caption    =\n|pushpin_mapsize        =\n|coor_pinpoint = Huangshan municipal government\n|coordinates = {{coord|29.7149|N|118.3376|E|type:adm2nd_region:CN-34_source:Gaode|format=dms|display=it}}\n<!-- Location ------------------>\n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name = [[China|People's Republic of China]]\n|subdivision_type1      = [[Province (China)|Province]]\n|subdivision_name1      = [[Anhui]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Administrative divisions of the People's Republic of China#County level|County-level divisions]]\n|subdivision_name2      =  7\n|subdivision_type3      = [[Administrative divisions of the People's Republic of China#Township level|Township-level divisions]]\n|subdivision_name3      =  145\n|subdivision_type4      = \n|subdivision_name4      = \n|seat_type              = Municipal seat\n|seat                   =[[Tunxi District]]\n<!-- Politics ----------------->\n|government_footnotes   =\n|government_type        =\n|leader_title           =CPC Secretary\n|leader_name            =\tWang Qimin ({{lang|zh-hans|\u738b\u542f\u654f}})\n|leader_title1          =[[Mayor]]\n|leader_name1           =\tLi Hongming ({{lang|zh-hans|\u674e\u5b8f\u9e23}})\n|established_title      =  <!-- Settled -->\n|established_date       = \n|established_title1     =  <!-- Incorporated (town) -->\n|established_date1      = \n|established_title2     = <!-- Incorporated (city) --> \n|established_date2      = \n|established_title3     =  \n|established_date3      =\n|named_for              =\n<!-- Area    --------------------->\n|unit_pref                = <!--Enter: Imperial, to display imperial before metric-->\n|area_footnotes           =\n|area_total_km2           =9807.4 <!-- ALL fields with measurements are subject to automatic unit conversion-->\n|area_land_km2            = \n|area_water_km2           = \n|area_water_percent       =\n|area_urban_km2           =\n|area_metro_km2           =\n<!-- Elevation -------------------------->\n|elevation_footnotes    =  <!--for references: use <ref> </ref> tags-->\n|elevation_m            = \n|elevation_ft           =\n|elevation_max_m            = \n|elevation_max_ft           =\n|elevation_min_m            = \n|elevation_min_ft           =\n<!-- Population   ----------------------->\n|population_as_of               = \n|population_footnotes           =\n|population_note                =\n|population_total               =   1470000\n|population_density_km2         =auto\n|population_metro               =\n|population_density_metro_km2   =\n|population_urban               =\n|population_density_urban_km2   = \n|population_blank1_title        =\n|population_blank1              =\n|population_density_blank1_km2  =\n<!-- General information  --------------->\n|timezone               = [[China Standard Time|CST]]\n|utc_offset             = +8\n \n \n<!-- Area/postal codes & others -------->\n|postal_code_type       = <!--  [[Postal code of China|Postal code]] -->\n|postal_code            = 245000\n|area_code              = 0559\n|iso_code = [[ISO 3166-2:CN|CN-AH-10]]\n|blank_name             =[[GDP]] \n|blank_info             =\n|blank1_name            =GDP per capita  \n|blank1_info            = \n|blank2_name            =[[Licence plates of the People's Republic of China|License Plate]] Prefix \n|blank2_info            ={{lang|zh-cn|\u7696J}}\n|blank3_name            =<!-- Major [[Nationalities of China|Nationalities]] -->\n|blank3_info            =\n|website                = {{url|http://www.huangshan.gov.cn}}\n|footnotes              =\n}}\n\n'''Huangshan''' ({{zh|s={{linktext|\u9ec4\u5c71}} |t={{linktext|\u9ec3\u5c71}} |p={{linktext|Hu\u00e1ngsh\u0101n}}}}), is a [[prefecture-level city]] in southern [[Anhui]] province, People's Republic of China.  Huangshan means ''Yellow Mountain'' in Chinese and the city is named after the famously scenic [[Huangshan|Yellow Mountains]] which cover much of the city's vast geographic expanse.  The prefectural city of Huangshan includes three urban districts and four counties.  The urban center of Huangshan was originally the city of '''Tunxi''', and is now called [[Tunxi District]].  Locals still call the city Tunxi to distinguish urban core from other parts of Huangshan.\n\t\nHuangshan occupies the southernmost part of Anhui. It is bordered by [[Chizhou]] to the northwest, [[Xuancheng]] to the northeast, [[Jiangxi]] Province to the southwest and [[Zhejiang]] Province to the southeast.  Huangshan's history dates back to the time of the [[First Emperor]].  The city's current jurisdiction covers much of the historical and cultural region of [[Huizhou (region)|Huizhou]] ({{lang|zh|\u5fbd\u5dde}}), which together with [[Anqing]] formed the name of Anhui Province. Huangshan is home to two [[UNESCO]] [[World Heritage Sites]], [[Mount Huangshan]] and [[Ancient Villages in Southern Anhui - Xidi and Hongcun|Hongcun and Xidi, the ancient villages of southern Anhui]].  It is a leading tourist destination in China.\n\n== Administration ==\n[[File:Loujiepailou.jpg|thumb|right|An old gate in the city]]\n\nThe [[prefecture-level city]] of Huangshan administers 7 [[Administrative divisions of the People's Republic of China#County level|county-level divisions]], including 3 [[District of China|districts]] and 4 [[County (People's Republic of China)|counties]].\n\n* [[Tunxi District]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u5c6f\u6eaa\u533a}})\n* [[Huangshan District]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u9ec4\u5c71\u533a}})\n* [[Huizhou District]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u5fbd\u5dde\u533a}})\n* [[She County, Anhui|She County]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u6b59\u53bf}})\n* [[Xiuning County]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u4f11\u5b81\u53bf}})\n* [[Yi County, Anhui|Yi County]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u9edf\u53bf}})\n* [[Qimen County]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u7941\u95e8\u53bf}})\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n!Map\n|-\n|<div style=\"position: relative\" class=\"center\">\n{{Image label begin|image=Administrative Division Huangshan.png|width=666|link=}} \n{{Image label|x=1390|y=1180|scale=666/2220|text=[[Tunxi District|'''Tunxi''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=1070|y=420|scale=666/2220|text=[[Huangshan District|'''Huangshan''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=1280|y=900|scale=666/2220|text=[[Huizhou District|'''Huizhou''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=1760|y=1000|scale=666/2220|text=[[She County, Anhui|'''She<br/>County''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=1080|y=1260|scale=666/2220|text=[[Xiuning County|'''Xiuning<br/>County''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=850|y=740|scale=666/2220|text=[[Yi County, Anhui|'''Yi<br/>County''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=500|y=980|scale=666/2220|text=[[Qimen County|'''Qimen<br/>County''']]}}\n</div>\n|}\n\nThese are further divided into 145 [[Administrative divisions of the People's Republic of China#Township level|township-level divisions]], including 42 [[town of China|towns]], 100 [[Township (People's Republic of China)|townships]] and 3 [[subdistrict]]s.\n\n== Economy ==\n[[File:Qimen Hao Ya.jpg|thumb|right|180px|Keemun tea]]\n[[Keemun tea]] is produced in [[Qimen County]], and the tea is named for the county. [[Mao feng]], a green tea, is produced in neighboring counties. Tourism, centered on [[Mount Huang]] and including other scenic and historic sites (such as [[Xidi]] and [[Hongcun]]), is an important part of the Huangshan economy.\n\n==Transportation==\nDue to rugged terrain, Huangshan was traditionally a secluded region.  The Xinan River provided an outlet to the east.  Winding, narrow roads through Huang Mountains made trips to Xuancheng, Wuhu, Guichi and the Yangtze River slow and arduous.  In recent decades, improvements to the transportation infrastructure have made the city and its surrounding tourist attractions more accessible.\n\n===Air===\nThe [[Huangshan Tunxi International Airport]], also referred to as the Tunxi Airport, is located in Tunxi District and is known by the IATA abbreviation '''TXN'''.  The airport was built in 1958 and was expanded in 2000.  It offers daily flights to Beijing, Shanghai, Hefei, Guangzhou, and weekly flights to Chengdu, Chongqing, Xiamen, and Shenzhen.\n\n===Rail===\n[[File:Huangshan train station.jpg|thumb|right|250px|The Huangshan Train Station.]]\nHuangshan City is currently served by only one railway line, the [[Anhui\u2013Jiangxi Railway]], which was completed in 1982 and has stations in Jixi County, She County, Tunxi District, Xiuning County, and Qimen County.  From the main Huangshan City Railway Station in Tunxi, direct train service is available to Nanjing, Shanghai, Bengbu, Huaibei, Qingdao and Beijing among other cities the north, and points to the south including Jingdezhen, Yingtan, Fuzhou, Xiamen, Guangzhou, Shenzhen, and Kunming.\n\nHuangshan is accessible via high-speed rail through the [[Hefei\u2013Fuzhou high-speed railway]] and the [[Hangzhou\u2013Huangshan intercity railway]].\n\n===Road===\nHuangshan is now a highway junction city.  The Huizhou-Hangzhou Expressway runs east to Hanghzou.  The Hefei-Tongling-Huangshan Expressway heads north to Tongling on the Yangtze River and then to Hefei, the Anhui provincial capital.  The Huangshan-Taling-Taolin Expressway extends southwest to Wuyuan in Jiangxi Province.  The Huangshan-Quzhou-Nanping Expressway, currently under construction, will run southeast through Zhejiang Province to Nanping in Fujian Province.  Until the expressways were built in the first decade of the 21st century, Huangshan's main roads were National Route G205 and Provincial Route S326, which follow the Anhui-Zhejiang Railway.\n\n==Cultural history==\n[[File:Ancient Villages in Southern Anhui \u2013 Xidi and Hongcun-114145.jpg|thumb|Ancient Villages in Southern Anhui \u2013 [[Xidi]] and [[Hongcun]].]]\nIn the Ming dynasty, {{ill|Zheng Zhizhen|zh|\u912d\u4e4b\u73cd}} ({{zh|labels=no|t=\u912d\u4e4b\u73cd}}; 1518&ndash;1595), a native of the [[Huizhou District|Huizhou]], [[Anhui]],  village of [[Qingxi, Anhui|Qingxi]] wrote the opera ''[[Mulian Rescues His Mother]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.worldcat.org/title/xin-ke-chu-xiang-yin-zhu-quan-shan-mulian-jiu-mu-xing-xiao-xi-wen-8-juan/oclc/44465384&referer=brief_results |script-title=zh:\u65b0\u523b\u51fa\u76f8\u97f3\u8a3b\u52f8\u5584\u76ee\u84ee\u6551\u6bcd\u884c\u5b5d\u6232\u6587 : 8\u5377 |publisher=[[WorldCat]] |accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref>[http://www.wdl.org/en/item/7110/ Mulian Rescues His Mother]  [[World Digital Library]].</ref> According to local legend, Zheng was blind when he wrote the opera and was restored to full sight by a grateful [[Guanyin]] (the legend also has it that when Zheng later wrote a love story he went blind again). {{sfnb|Guo|2005| p = [https://books.google.com/books?id=lJWTY9dIs5oC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q=according%20local%20legend%20Zhizhen&f=false 89]}}\n\nIn 2011, Local authorities promoted performance of the Ming dynasty play ''Mulian Rescues His Mother'' as a tourist attraction.<ref>[http://www.womenofchina.cn/womenofchina/html1/culture/arts/12/8159-1.htm Mulian Opera 'Ghost Drama' Revival] [http://www.womenofchina.cn/ Women of China] March 24, 2011.</ref>\n\n== Other notes ==\nIn early 2008, the BBC broadcast a series of 5 documentaries on life for schoolchildren in China, called \"Chinese School\". One of the three schools documented was [[Xiuning High School]], the top school in the county. This was situated in the town of Xiuning, in the county of Xiuning in Huangshan.\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References and further reading==\n* {{cite book |last = Guo  |first = Qitao  |year = 2005 |title = Ritual Opera and Mercantile Lineage: The Confucian Transformation of Popular Culture in Late Imperial Huizhou |publisher = Stanford University Press| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=lJWTY9dIs5oC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|location = Stanford, Calif. |isbn = 0804750327 |ref = harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Huangshan (city)}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20081226015848/http://www.huangshan.gov.cn/ Official website]\n*[http://www.go2huangshan.com Huangshan Tours and Hotels]\n*[http://pem.org/yinyutang/  '' Yin Yu Tang: A Chinese Home ''] provides a detailed look at life within the Huangshan District of East China through the examination of a Huang family residence built during the late Qing dynasty and occupied for over 200 years.\n\n{{Anhui topics}}\n{{Anhui}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Cities in Anhui]]\n[[Category:Huangshan City]]\n", "text_old": "{{More footnotes|date=March 2014}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|name                   = {{raise|0.2em|Huangshan}}\n|native_name            = {{lower|0.1em|{{nobold|{{lang|zh-hans|\u9ec4\u5c71\u5e02}}}}}}\n|official_name          = \n|nickname               = \n|settlement_type        =[[Prefecture-level city]]\n|total_type             = <!-- to set a non-standard label for total area and population rows -->\n|motto                  =\n<!-- images and maps  ----------->\n|image_skyline          = HuangShanCity.JPG\n|imagesize              = \n|image_caption          = Reconstructed old town, Song Street\n|image_map              =  Location of Huangshan Prefecture within Anhui (China).png\n|mapsize                =  \n|map_caption            =  \n|image_map1             = \n|mapsize1               = \n|map_caption1           = \n|image_dot_map          =\n|dot_mapsize            =\n|dot_map_caption        =\n|dot_x =  |dot_y =\n|pushpin_map            = \n|pushpin_label_position = \n|pushpin_map_caption    =\n|pushpin_mapsize        =\n<!-- Location ------------------>\n|coordinates            = \n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name = [[China|People's Republic of China]]\n|subdivision_type1      = [[Province (China)|Province]]\n|subdivision_name1      = [[Anhui]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Administrative divisions of the People's Republic of China#County level|County-level divisions]]\n|subdivision_name2      =  7\n|subdivision_type3      = [[Administrative divisions of the People's Republic of China#Township level|Township-level divisions]]\n|subdivision_name3      =  145\n|subdivision_type4      = \n|subdivision_name4      = \n|seat_type              = Municipal seat\n|seat                   =[[Tunxi District]]{{coord|29|42|N|118|18|E|display=title}}\n<!-- Politics ----------------->\n|government_footnotes   =\n|government_type        =\n|leader_title           =CPC Secretary\n|leader_name            =\tWang Qimin ({{lang|zh-hans|\u738b\u542f\u654f}})\n|leader_title1          =[[Mayor]]\n|leader_name1           =\tLi Hongming ({{lang|zh-hans|\u674e\u5b8f\u9e23}})\n|established_title      =  <!-- Settled -->\n|established_date       = \n|established_title1     =  <!-- Incorporated (town) -->\n|established_date1      = \n|established_title2     = <!-- Incorporated (city) --> \n|established_date2      = \n|established_title3     =  \n|established_date3      =\n|named_for              =\n<!-- Area    --------------------->\n|unit_pref                = <!--Enter: Imperial, to display imperial before metric-->\n|area_footnotes           =\n|area_total_km2           =9807.4 <!-- ALL fields with measurements are subject to automatic unit conversion-->\n|area_land_km2            = \n|area_water_km2           = \n|area_water_percent       =\n|area_urban_km2           =\n|area_urban_sq_mi         =\n|area_metro_km2           =\n|area_metro_sq_mi         =\n<!-- Elevation -------------------------->\n|elevation_footnotes    =  <!--for references: use <ref> </ref> tags-->\n|elevation_m            = \n|elevation_ft           =\n|elevation_max_m            = \n|elevation_max_ft           =\n|elevation_min_m            = \n|elevation_min_ft           =\n<!-- Population   ----------------------->\n|population_as_of               = \n|population_footnotes           =\n|population_note                =\n|population_total               =   1470000\n|population_density_km2         =auto\n|population_metro               =\n|population_density_metro_km2   =\n|population_urban               =\n|population_density_urban_km2   = \n|population_blank1_title        =\n|population_blank1              =\n|population_density_blank1_km2  =\n<!-- General information  --------------->\n|timezone               = [[China Standard Time|CST]]\n|utc_offset             = +8\n \n \n| coor_type             = <!-- can be used to specify what the coordinates refer to -->\n<!-- Area/postal codes & others -------->\n|postal_code_type       = <!--  [[Postal code of China|Postal code]] -->\n|postal_code            = 245000\n|area_code              = 0559\n|iso_code = [[ISO 3166-2:CN|CN-AH-10]]\n|blank_name             =[[GDP]] \n|blank_info             =\n|blank1_name            =GDP per capita  \n|blank1_info            = \n|blank2_name            =[[Licence plates of the People's Republic of China|License Plate]] Prefix \n|blank2_info            ={{lang|zh-cn|\u7696J}}\n|blank3_name            =<!-- Major [[Nationalities of China|Nationalities]] -->\n|blank3_info            =\n|website                = {{url|http://www.huangshan.gov.cn}}\n|footnotes              =\n}}\n\n'''Huangshan''' ({{zh|s={{linktext|\u9ec4\u5c71}} |t={{linktext|\u9ec3\u5c71}} |p={{linktext|Hu\u00e1ngsh\u0101n}}}}), is a [[prefecture-level city]] in southern [[Anhui]] province, People's Republic of China.  Huangshan means ''Yellow Mountain'' in Chinese and the city is named after the famously scenic [[Huangshan|Yellow Mountains]] which cover much of the city's vast geographic expanse.  The prefectural city of Huangshan includes three urban districts and four counties.  The urban center of Huangshan was originally the city of '''Tunxi''', and is now called [[Tunxi District]].  Locals still call the city Tunxi to distinguish urban core from other parts of Huangshan.\n\t\nHuangshan occupies the southernmost part of Anhui. It is bordered by [[Chizhou]] to the northwest, [[Xuancheng]] to the northeast, [[Jiangxi]] Province to the southwest and [[Zhejiang]] Province to the southeast.  Huangshan's history dates back to the time of the [[First Emperor]].  The city's current jurisdiction covers much of the historical and cultural region of [[Huizhou (region)|Huizhou]] ({{lang|zh|\u5fbd\u5dde}}), which together with [[Anqing]] formed the name of Anhui Province. Huangshan is home to two [[UNESCO]] [[World Heritage Sites]], [[Mount Huangshan]] and [[Ancient Villages in Southern Anhui - Xidi and Hongcun|Hongcun and Xidi, the ancient villages of southern Anhui]].  It is a leading tourist destination in China.\n\n== Administration ==\n[[File:Loujiepailou.jpg|thumb|right|An old gate in the city]]\n\nThe [[prefecture-level city]] of Huangshan administers 7 [[Administrative divisions of the People's Republic of China#County level|county-level divisions]], including 3 [[District of China|districts]] and 4 [[County (People's Republic of China)|counties]].\n\n* [[Tunxi District]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u5c6f\u6eaa\u533a}})\n* [[Huangshan District]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u9ec4\u5c71\u533a}})\n* [[Huizhou District]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u5fbd\u5dde\u533a}})\n* [[She County, Anhui|She County]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u6b59\u53bf}})\n* [[Xiuning County]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u4f11\u5b81\u53bf}})\n* [[Yi County, Anhui|Yi County]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u9edf\u53bf}})\n* [[Qimen County]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u7941\u95e8\u53bf}})\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n!Map\n|-\n|<div style=\"position: relative\" class=\"center\">\n{{Image label begin|image=Administrative Division Huangshan.png|width=666|link=}} \n{{Image label|x=1390|y=1180|scale=666/2220|text=[[Tunxi District|'''Tunxi''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=1070|y=420|scale=666/2220|text=[[Huangshan District|'''Huangshan''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=1280|y=900|scale=666/2220|text=[[Huizhou District|'''Huizhou''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=1760|y=1000|scale=666/2220|text=[[She County, Anhui|'''She<br>County''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=1080|y=1260|scale=666/2220|text=[[Xiuning County|'''Xiuning<br>County''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=850|y=740|scale=666/2220|text=[[Yi County, Anhui|'''Yi<br>County''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=500|y=980|scale=666/2220|text=[[Qimen County|'''Qimen<br>County''']]}}\n</div>\n|}\n\nThese are further divided into 145 [[Administrative divisions of the People's Republic of China#Township level|township-level divisions]], including 42 [[town of China|towns]], 100 [[Township (People's Republic of China)|townships]] and 3 [[subdistrict]]s.\n\n== Economy ==\n[[File:Qimen Hao Ya.jpg|thumb|right|180px|Keemun tea]]\n[[Keemun tea]] is produced in [[Qimen County]], and the tea is named for the county. [[Mao feng]], a green tea, is produced in neighboring counties. Tourism, centered on [[Mount Huang]] and including other scenic and historic sites (such as [[Xidi]] and [[Hongcun]]), is an important part of the Huangshan economy.\n\n==Transportation==\nDue to rugged terrain, Huangshan was traditionally a secluded region.  The Xinan River provided an outlet to the east.  Winding, narrow roads through Huang Mountains made trips to Xuancheng, Wuhu, Guichi and the Yangtze River slow and arduous.  In recent decades, improvements to the transportation infrastructure have made the city and its surrounding tourist attractions more accessible.\n\n===Air===\nThe [[Huangshan Tunxi International Airport]], also referred to as the Tunxi Airport, is located in Tunxi District and is known by the IATA abbreviation '''TXN'''.  The airport was built in 1958 and was expanded in 2000.  It offers daily flights to Beijing, Shanghai, Hefei, Guangzhou, and weekly flights to Chengdu, Chongqing, Xiamen, and Shenzhen.\n\n===Rail===\n[[File:Huangshan train station.jpg|thumb|right|250px|The Huangshan Train Station.]]\nHuangshan City is currently served by only one railway line, the [[Anhui\u2013Jiangxi Railway]], which was completed in 1982 and has stations in Jixi County, She County, Tunxi District, Xiuning County, and Qimen County.  From the main Huangshan City Railway Station in Tunxi, direct train service is available to Nanjing, Shanghai, Bengbu, Huaibei, Qingdao and Beijing among other cities the north, and points to the south including Jingdezhen, Yingtan, Fuzhou, Xiamen, Guangzhou, Shenzhen, and Kunming.\n\nHuangshan is accessible via high-speed rail through the [[Hefei\u2013Fuzhou high-speed railway]] and the [[Hangzhou\u2013Huangshan intercity railway]].\n\n===Road===\nHuangshan is now a highway junction city.  The Huizhou-Hangzhou Expressway runs east to Hanghzou.  The Hefei-Tongling-Huangshan Expressway heads north to Tongling on the Yangtze River and then to Hefei, the Anhui provincial capital.  The Huangshan-Taling-Taolin Expressway extends southwest to Wuyuan in Jiangxi Province.  The Huangshan-Quzhou-Nanping Expressway, currently under construction, will run southeast through Zhejiang Province to Nanping in Fujian Province.  Until the expressways were built in the first decade of the 21st century, Huangshan's main roads were National Route G205 and Provincial Route S326, which follow the Anhui-Zhejiang Railway.\n\n==Cultural history==\n[[File:Ancient Villages in Southern Anhui \u2013 Xidi and Hongcun-114145.jpg|thumb|Ancient Villages in Southern Anhui \u2013 [[Xidi]] and [[Hongcun]].]]\nIn the Ming dynasty, {{ill|Zheng Zhizhen|zh|\u912d\u4e4b\u73cd}}  \u912d\u4e4b\u73cd (1518-1595), a native of the [[Huizhou District|Huizhou]], [[Anhui]],  village of [[Qingxi, Anhui|Qingxi]] wrote the opera [http://www.worldcat.org/title/xin-ke-chu-xiang-yin-zhu-quan-shan-mulian-jiu-mu-xing-xiao-xi-wen-8-juan/oclc/44465384&referer=brief_results  \u76ee\u84ee\u6551\u6bcd\u884c\u5b5d\u6232\u6587 Mulian jiu mu xing xiao xi wen (Mulian rescues his mother)].<ref>[http://www.wdl.org/en/item/7110/ Mulian Rescues His Mother]  [[World Digital Library]].</ref> According to local legend, Zheng was blind when he wrote the opera and was restored to full sight by a grateful [[Guanyin]] (the legend also has it that when Zheng later wrote a love story he went blind again). {{sfnb|Guo|2005| p = [https://books.google.com/books?id=lJWTY9dIs5oC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q=according%20local%20legend%20Zhizhen&f=false 89]}}\n\nIn 2011, Local authorities promoted performance of the Ming dynasty play [[Mulian Rescues His Mother]] as a tourist attraction.<ref>[http://www.womenofchina.cn/womenofchina/html1/culture/arts/12/8159-1.htm Mulian Opera 'Ghost Drama' Revival] [http://www.womenofchina.cn/ Women of China] March 24, 2011.</ref>\n\n== Other notes ==\nIn early 2008, the BBC broadcast a series of 5 documentaries on life for schoolchildren in China, called \"Chinese School\". One of the three schools documented was [[Xiuning High School]], the top school in the county. This was situated in the town of Xiuning, in the county of Xiuning in Huangshan.\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References and further reading==\n* {{cite book |last = Guo  |first = Qitao  |year = 2005 |title = Ritual Opera and Mercantile Lineage: The Confucian Transformation of Popular Culture in Late Imperial Huizhou |publisher = Stanford University Press| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=lJWTY9dIs5oC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|location = Stanford, Calif. |isbn = 0804750327 |ref = harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Huangshan (city)}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20081226015848/http://www.huangshan.gov.cn/ Official website]\n*[http://www.go2huangshan.com Huangshan Tours and Hotels]\n*[http://pem.org/yinyutang/  '' Yin Yu Tang: A Chinese Home ''] provides a detailed look at life within the Huangshan District of East China through the examination of a Huang family residence built during the late Qing dynasty and occupied for over 200 years.\n\n{{Anhui topics}}\n{{Anhui}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Cities in Anhui]]\n[[Category:Huangshan City]]\n", "name_user": "CaradhrasAiguo", "label": "safe", "comment": "Ref work: script-title, quote, zh in Publisher, etc", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Huangshan_City"}
{"title_page": "Rollatini", "text_new": "{{short description|Italian-style dish}}\n{{Infobox prepared food\n| name             = Rollatini\n| image            = Eggplant_rollatini.jpg\n| image_size       = 250px\n| caption          = \n| alternate_name   = Involtini\n| country          = Italy\n| region           = \n| creator          = \n| course           = \n| type             = \n| served           = \n| main_ingredient  = [[Eggplant]] or [[veal]] or [[Chicken (food)|chicken]] or [[Fish (food)|fish]], [[ricotta]]\n| variations       = \n| calories         = 20\n| other            = \n}}\n\n'''Rollatini''' (sometimes also spelled '''rolatini''' or '''rolletini''') is an [[Italian cuisine|Italian]]-style dish (called ''rollatini di melanzane'' in faux [[Italian language|Italian]]) that is usually made with thin slices of [[eggplant]], which are dusted in [[wheat flour]] or lightly [[Breading|breaded]] and covered with [[ricotta]] and often other cheeses and seasonings, then rolled up and baked. Alternatively, [[veal]], [[chicken]], or [[Fish (food)|fish]] may be used in place of the eggplant.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rKaTBAAAQBAJ|title=Patsy's Italian Family Cookbook|last=Scognamillo|first=Sal|date=2015-03-24|publisher=St. Martin's Press|isbn=9781250039408|page=25|language=en}}</ref>\n\n''Rollatini'' is not an actual [[Italian language|Italian]] word; in Italy the dish is known as ''involtini'' (e.g., ''involtini di melanzane'').<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==See also==\n* [[Braciola]]\n* [[Chicken piccata]]\n* [[Eggplant parmesan]]\n* [[List of eggplant dishes]]\n* [[List of Italian dishes]]\n* [[Scaloppine]]\n* {{portal-inline|Food}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080326100641/http://www.foodnetwork.com/food/recipes/recipe/0,1977,FOOD_9936_22336,00.html Eggplant rollatini recipe] from ''[[Everyday Italian]]'', by [[Giada De Laurentiis|Giada de Laurentiis]]\n\n{{eggplant dishes}}\n\n[[Category:Beef dishes]]\n[[Category:Italian chicken dishes]]\n[[Category:Italian-American chicken dishes]]\n[[Category:Eggplant dishes]]\n[[Category:Italian cuisine]]\n[[Category:Italian-American cuisine]]\n[[Category:Baked goods]]\n\n\n{{Italy-cuisine-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox prepared food\n| name             = Rollatini\n| image            = Eggplant_rollatini.jpg\n| image_size       = 250px\n| caption          = \n| alternate_name   = Involtini\n| country          = Italy\n| region           = \n| creator          = \n| course           = \n| type             = \n| served           = \n| main_ingredient  = [[Eggplant]] or [[veal]] or [[Chicken (food)|chicken]] or [[Fish (food)|fish]], [[ricotta]]\n| variations       = \n| calories         = 20\n| other            = \n}}\n\n'''Rollatini''' (sometimes also spelled '''rolatini''' or '''rolletini''') is an [[Italian cuisine|Italian]]-style dish (called ''rollatini di melanzane'' in faux [[Italian language|Italian]]) that is usually made with thin slices of [[eggplant]], which are dusted in [[wheat flour]] or lightly [[Breading|breaded]] and covered with [[ricotta]] and often other cheeses and seasonings, then rolled up and baked. Alternatively, [[veal]], [[chicken]], or [[Fish (food)|fish]] may be used in place of the eggplant.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rKaTBAAAQBAJ|title=Patsy's Italian Family Cookbook|last=Scognamillo|first=Sal|date=2015-03-24|publisher=St. Martin's Press|isbn=9781250039408|page=25|language=en}}</ref>\n\n''Rollatini'' is not an actual [[Italian language|Italian]] word; in Italy the dish is known as ''involtini'' (e.g., ''involtini di melanzane'').<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==See also==\n* [[Braciola]]\n* [[Chicken piccata]]\n* [[Eggplant parmesan]]\n* [[List of eggplant dishes]]\n* [[List of Italian dishes]]\n* [[Scaloppine]]\n* {{portal-inline|Food}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080326100641/http://www.foodnetwork.com/food/recipes/recipe/0,1977,FOOD_9936_22336,00.html Eggplant rollatini recipe] from ''[[Everyday Italian]]'', by [[Giada De Laurentiis|Giada de Laurentiis]]\n\n{{eggplant dishes}}\n\n[[Category:Beef dishes]]\n[[Category:Italian chicken dishes]]\n[[Category:Italian-American chicken dishes]]\n[[Category:Eggplant dishes]]\n[[Category:Italian cuisine]]\n[[Category:Italian-American cuisine]]\n[[Category:Baked goods]]\n\n\n{{Italy-cuisine-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Erpert", "label": "safe", "comment": "description", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rollatini"}
